chunks.html_content:
You can apply for a birth registration correction when the information is wrong - for example if a mistake was made when recording a parent’s occupation.

You cannot apply for a correction to show new information if circumstances change after you’ve registered your child’s birth, for example if you change your name after getting married again.

However, you can apply to re-register the birth if the natural parents get married at a later date.

You can apply to change who the recorded father is if you can prove that the man named on the certificate is not the natural father of the child. Examples of proof include:

  • a DNA test record from an approved tester
  • a court order
  • evidence that confirms the name of the true biological father
  • other evidence that confirms the recorded father could not have been the child’s natural father

Correct a birth registration
Removing the wrong father’s details

heading_context: What happens if you change gender
chunks.html_content: If you get your gender change legally recognised, you’ll be able to order a new birth certificate with your new gender on it.
chunks.plain_content:
Correct a birth registration
What happens if you change gender
If you get your gender change legally recognised, you’ll be able to order a new birth certificate with your new gender on it.

chunks.html_content:
If your application is approved, a correction is made in the register in the office for the area where your child was born.

The original information will always be shown in the register. After the correction has been authorised, a note will be added to the margin of the register. This will explain what the correct information is and when the correction was made.

All full birth certificates that are issued after the correction will include the note in the margin.

Short birth certificates only include the child’s details and will not have a note in the margin - they just show any correct new details.
chunks.plain_content:
Correct a birth registration
What the correction looks like

chunks.html_content:
The following people can apply for a correction:

  • the mother
  • the father (if his details are on the certificate)
chunks.plain_content:
Correct a birth registration
The following people can apply for a correction:

  the mother
  the father (if his details are on the certificate)

chunks.html_content: If you’re applying to change a child’s name and both parents are named on the certificate, both must sign the application form.
chunks.plain_content:
Correct a birth registration
If you’re applying to change a child’s name and both parents are named on the certificate, both must sign the application form.

chunks.html_content:
The child named on the certificate may be able to apply for a correction if their parents are not available.

It is not always necessary for the named father to take part in the correction process. The General Register Office (GRO) can correct the entry if 2 of the following people apply to have it changed:

  • the mother
  • the natural father
  • the man named on the birth certificate as the father

At least one of these must sign the application form.

You need to provide contact addresses for the mother, the man named as the father on the certificate and the true biological father (if he took part in a DNA test).

chunks.html_content:
It costs £75 or £90 to apply to correct a mistake in a birth registration.

Contact the register office where your child’s birth was registered to find out how to send your application, the cost and how to pay.

Fill in the relevant application form and send it to the register office:

  • correct details on a birth registration
  • remove incorrect father’s details from a birth registration

chunks.html_content: There’s a different process for correcting registrations made in Northern Ireland and correcting registrations made in Scotland.
chunks.plain_content:
Correct a birth registration

chunks.html_content:
You’ll need to show that the information given at the time of the registration was wrong. You must send in documents with your application that show what the correct information should have been. These documents should be valid or dated around the time your child was born.

Documents you can send in include a:

  • passport
  • photocard driving licence
  • bank, building society or credit card statement
  • letter from a hospital or doctor
  • letter from a government department
chunks.plain_content:
Correct a birth registration
Proving the registration is wrong

Documents you can send in include a:

  passport
  photocard driving licence
  bank, building society or credit card statement
  letter from a hospital or doctor
  letter from a government department

chunks.html_content: If you are not able to send in proof, corrections cannot usually be made.
chunks.plain_content:
Correct a birth registration
Proving the registration is wrong
If you are not able to send in proof, corrections cannot usually be made.

heading_context: Proof the wrong father is on the certificate
chunks.html_content:
All certified copies sent with the application will be destroyed if you do not ask for them to be returned.

You’ll need to prove that the man named on the certificate is not the natural father of the child. Examples of proof include:

  • a DNA test record from an approved tester
  • a court order
  • evidence that confirms the name of the true biological father
  • other evidence that confirms the recorded father could not have been the child’s natural father

Correct a birth registration
Proving the registration is wrong
Proof the wrong father is on the certificate

  a court order
  evidence that confirms the name of the true biological father
  other evidence that confirms the recorded father could not have been the child’s natural father

chunks.html_content: You should only send in documents that have been certified as true copies of the original.
chunks.plain_content:
Correct a birth registration
Sending in certified documents
You should only send in documents that have been certified as true copies of the original.

chunks.html_content: If you’re applying to correct a serious mistake (such as the name of a person), the General Register Office (GRO) may ask you to make a ‘statutory declaration’ about the correction and send it to them. This means you have to make a legal statement in front of someone like a judge or solicitor that they must sign (sometimes called ‘attesting an oath’).
chunks.plain_content:
Correct a birth registration
Statutory declaration
If you’re applying to correct a serious mistake (such as the name of a person), the General Register Office (GRO) may ask you to make a ‘statutory declaration’ about the correction and send it to them. This means you have to make a legal statement in front of someone like a judge or solicitor that they must sign (sometimes called ‘attesting an oath’).

chunks.html_content: You may have to pay a fee for a statutory declaration.
chunks.plain_content:
Correct a birth registration
Statutory declaration
You may have to pay a fee for a statutory declaration.

chunks.html_content: There is no set time for how long applications will take. It can take up to 25 days for you to get a reply.
chunks.plain_content:
Correct a birth registration
How long applications take 
There is no set time for how long applications will take. It can take up to 25 days for you to get a reply.

chunks.html_content:
The register office or GRO will tell you when they’ve approved the correction.

You can then buy a full birth certificate which will show the original information and a note of the corrected details.
chunks.plain_content:
Correct a birth registration
If the correction is approved
The register office or GRO will tell you when they’ve approved the correction.
You can then buy a full birth certificate which will show the original information and a note of the corrected details.

chunks.html_content: If you want further advice on applying to make a correction, contact the register office or the General Register Office (GRO).
chunks.plain_content:
Correct a birth registration
Advice
If you want further advice on applying to make a correction, contact the register office or the General Register Office (GRO).
